00:01:50.069 --> 00:01:52.900
So this is the brain of
a bottlenose dolphin,

00:01:52.900 --> 00:01:54.170
the back of the brain
of a bottlenose dolphin

00:01:54.170 --> 00:01:55.770
and this is the brain of a small marsupial

00:01:55.770 --> 00:01:57.870
and you can see the
neocortex is really large

00:01:57.870 --> 00:01:59.793
and I'm gonna talk about
the neocortex today,

00:01:59.793 --> 00:02:02.030
very specifically for a couple of reasons.

00:02:02.030 --> 00:02:04.262
One is that it's the part of the brain

00:02:04.262 --> 00:02:08.940
that's changed most dramatically
in mammals over time

00:02:08.940 --> 00:02:09.880
and in humans in particular,

00:02:09.880 --> 00:02:11.830
they have an extremely large neocortex.

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:13.210
It's the part of the brain

00:02:13.210 --> 00:02:15.429
that's involved in cognition, language,

00:02:15.429 --> 00:02:18.520
and things like tool use.

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:19.353
The question

00:02:19.353 --> 00:02:21.980
that we're interested in
addressing in my laboratory

00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:24.220
is how the brain gets more complex

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:26.060
or how the neocortex gets more complex.

00:02:26.060 --> 00:02:27.450
So we know that early mammals

00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:29.840
had a neocortex that was very, very tiny

00:02:29.840 --> 00:02:31.330
and had a few cortical fields.

00:02:31.330 --> 00:02:32.984
And cortical fields are
the functional units

00:02:32.984 --> 00:02:35.340
of the neocortex.

00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:37.615
And we know that as brains evolved,

00:02:37.615 --> 00:02:39.110
and particularly primate brains

00:02:39.110 --> 00:02:39.943
the neocortex became

00:02:39.943 --> 00:02:41.963
a really, really enormous cortical sheet

00:02:41.963 --> 00:02:43.650
that now is proposed,

00:02:43.650 --> 00:02:46.130
humans are proposed to have
hundreds of cortical fields.

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:47.820
So the question is how do you get

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:49.220
from a very, very simple form

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:50.810
to a very, very complicated form.

00:02:50.810 --> 00:02:53.080
But this is a serious problem to address

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:54.970
because these types of changes,

00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:55.990
certainly from early mammals,

00:02:55.990 --> 00:02:58.830
are 200 million years of changes.

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:00.830
And we can even see the sorts of changes

00:03:00.830 --> 00:03:02.230
that have occurred in the human line

00:03:02.230 --> 00:03:04.090
over a six million year period.

00:03:04.090 --> 00:03:05.410
So how do you address these changes?

00:03:05.410 --> 00:03:07.230
And there are two ways that you can get

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:09.992
at this question of evolution.

00:03:09.992 --> 00:03:12.400
You can say what has evolution produced?

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:14.420
And the way we can understand
what evolution has produced

00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:15.710
is we look at brains and bodies,

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:16.760
we do a comparative approach.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:18.450
So I can look at a lot of different brains

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:20.250
using a variety of different techniques,

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:21.567
electrophysiological, anatomical,

00:03:21.567 --> 00:03:24.635
and I can say, what sorts
of changes have come about?

00:03:24.635 --> 00:03:28.365
The problem is evolution
is a moving picture

00:03:28.365 --> 00:03:31.210
and the life of an individual
is a moving picture.

00:03:31.210 --> 00:03:34.860
So any time we study an
individual or a mammal,

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:37.610
we're taking one snapshot of
that moving picture of life

00:03:37.610 --> 00:03:39.030
and trying to figure it out.

00:03:39.030 --> 00:03:40.580
So what we do with a comparative analysis

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:42.470
is we look at a lot of snapshots

00:03:42.470 --> 00:03:44.541
and try to put this moving
picture back together.

00:03:44.541 --> 00:03:47.670
However, while these sort
of comparative studies

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:49.520
can tell us what evolution has produced,

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:52.350
they don't tell us how
phenotypic transformations occur,

00:03:52.350 --> 00:03:53.670
how do I get more cortical fields?

00:03:53.670 --> 00:03:55.390
How do I change connections of a cortex

00:03:55.390 --> 00:03:56.756
which in turn changes behavior?

00:03:56.756 --> 00:03:58.728
And this is where studies of development

00:03:58.728 --> 00:03:59.750
come into play

00:03:59.750 --> 00:04:02.700
because the evolution of any aspect

00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:03.925
of the body, the brain,

00:04:03.925 --> 00:04:06.610
is actually the evolution
of developmental mechanisms

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:08.637
that give rise to that
aspect of the phenotype.

00:04:08.637 --> 00:04:11.170
So my talk is gonna focus a little bit

00:04:11.170 --> 00:04:12.530
on this.

00:04:12.530 --> 00:04:13.970
So comparative analysis,

00:04:13.970 --> 00:04:15.230
this is many, many years of work.

00:04:15.230 --> 00:04:16.570
This is a cladogram

00:04:16.570 --> 00:04:17.730
and these are neocortices.

00:04:17.730 --> 00:04:18.990
And you're gonna see
these sort of cartoons

00:04:18.990 --> 00:04:20.290
throughout the talk.

00:04:20.290 --> 00:04:21.140
This is the neocortex.

00:04:21.140 --> 00:04:23.770
These red and blue and yellow areas

00:04:23.770 --> 00:04:25.180
indicate cortical fields.

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:27.110
And the most important
thing to take away from this

00:04:27.110 --> 00:04:28.930
is that you can have common ancestors,

00:04:28.930 --> 00:04:30.200
which we don't know about,

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:32.680
humans, macaque monkeys, cats, squirrels.

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:34.960
There is a constellation
of cortical fields

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:35.987
that all species possess,

00:04:35.987 --> 00:04:37.910
even in the absence of use,

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:39.070
and this is due to inheritance

00:04:39.070 --> 00:04:39.903
from a common ancestry

00:04:39.903 --> 00:04:41.750
and it's also due to the
way genes are deployed

00:04:41.750 --> 00:04:42.640
in development.

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:44.631
But that's gonna be a different story.

00:04:44.631 --> 00:04:47.110
So there are similarities in brains.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:49.760
My brain is very similar to
a mouse brain in some ways

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:50.890
but it's also very different.

00:04:50.890 --> 00:04:53.260
And here are some of
the sorts of differences

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:54.823
you're gonna see.

00:04:54.823 --> 00:04:55.700
This is a flattened view of the neocortex.

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:56.590
This is the front of the brain,

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:57.620
this is the top of the brain.

00:04:57.620 --> 00:04:58.900
This is a macaque monkey

00:04:58.900 --> 00:04:59.770
and this is a mouse.

00:04:59.770 --> 00:05:00.760
And they're not drawn to scale.

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:01.593
This would actually,

00:05:01.593 --> 00:05:04.910
this mouse neocortex would
be a little tiny portion

00:05:04.910 --> 00:05:06.147
of the macaque neocortex.

00:05:06.147 --> 00:05:07.380
And what we can see

00:05:07.380 --> 00:05:09.927
is that there are changes in
the size of the cortical sheet,

00:05:09.927 --> 00:05:11.943
there are changes in
cortical field number,

00:05:11.943 --> 00:05:15.020
there are changes in the
relative size of cortical fields.

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:16.940
There are changes in
the connection patterns

00:05:16.940 --> 00:05:18.660
of homologous cortical fields.

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:20.208
And of course the question is

00:05:20.208 --> 00:05:24.280
to what extent are these
differences due to genes

00:05:24.280 --> 00:05:26.050
that are intrinsic to
the developing neocortex?

00:05:26.050 --> 00:05:27.560
Have they changed in species over time?

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:28.750
And they probably have.

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:30.800
Genes associated with the
development of the body.

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:31.760
Because the body changes,

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:33.080
we use the body differently

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:34.747
and you cannot think about the brain

00:05:34.747 --> 00:05:36.210
without thinking about the body.

00:05:36.210 --> 00:05:37.490
There's a middle man there, right?

00:05:37.490 --> 00:05:38.685
The brain is not embodied itself.

00:05:38.685 --> 00:05:39.760
It needs the body

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:42.261
to provide all information
about the world.

00:05:42.261 --> 00:05:44.170
Epigenetic influences.

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:47.840
And by this I mean sensory-driven

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:49.901
or environmental or context-driven changes

00:05:49.901 --> 00:05:52.308
to the brain and the body.

00:05:52.308 --> 00:05:55.440
Or is it some combination
of these factors?

00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:58.600
Is any creature due to
just one sort of thing

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:01.240
or is it some sort of
combination in different species

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:03.000
over the course of evolution?

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.293
So I'm gonna give you some examples

00:06:04.293 --> 00:06:05.690
of comparative work

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:07.280
and changes in peripheral morphology

00:06:07.280 --> 00:06:08.962
that give us some clue

00:06:08.962 --> 00:06:12.240
about what the answer to that question is.

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:14.440
So this is one of my very
favorite examples on the planet.

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:15.840
It's a duck-billed platypus.

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:17.630
This is a real animal, this is the bill

00:06:17.630 --> 00:06:20.240
and what's really cool, yeah

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:22.150
and the reason I'm also
interested in the body

00:06:22.150 --> 00:06:25.000
is when I started working on
different animals in Australia,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:26.980
I had to catch every
single animal I worked on

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:29.270
and it gives you a really,
really great appreciation

00:06:29.270 --> 00:06:30.610
for the body and how important it is

00:06:30.610 --> 00:06:32.390
because they're hard to catch.

00:06:32.390 --> 00:06:34.190
Anyway, I digress.

00:06:34.190 --> 00:06:35.990
So what's really cool about the platypus

00:06:35.990 --> 00:06:38.300
is that it has mechanosensory receptors

00:06:38.300 --> 00:06:40.760
that are exquisitely sensitive to touch,

00:06:40.760 --> 00:06:43.660
inter-digits with electrosensory
receptors on its bill,

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:45.150
and when it does anything important,

00:06:45.150 --> 00:06:48.010
capture prey items, mate,

00:06:48.010 --> 00:06:50.010
it closes its eyes, its ears and its nose.

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:51.130
So all it has is a bill.

00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:52.500
And if you look at its neocortex

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:54.331
using electrophysiological
recording techniques,

00:06:54.331 --> 00:06:56.180
this is the front of the brain,

00:06:56.180 --> 00:06:58.360
this is the top of the brain,

00:06:58.360 --> 00:06:59.930
this is the representation of the bill

00:06:59.930 --> 00:07:00.792
on the cortical sheet.

00:07:00.792 --> 00:07:02.610
There are a number of cortical fields.

00:07:02.610 --> 00:07:04.921
So within the somatosensory cortex,

00:07:04.921 --> 00:07:07.419
it takes up about 90% of the entire

00:07:07.419 --> 00:07:09.640
representation of the
somatosensory cortex.

00:07:09.640 --> 00:07:11.180
And if you look at the cortex itself,

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:14.120
it takes up about 75% of
the entire cortical sheet.

00:07:14.120 --> 00:07:16.543
This animal is one big huge bill.

00:07:16.543 --> 00:07:18.520
And it's hard to imagine,

00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:20.180
this is called cortical magnification.

00:07:20.180 --> 00:07:22.600
And the question is is this due to genes

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:23.760
intrinsic to the neocortex

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:25.870
that have made this
cortex one big huge bill,

00:07:25.870 --> 00:07:26.703
changes to the body?

00:07:26.703 --> 00:07:29.250
It has to be to some extent
due to changes in the body.

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:31.459
The environment and how the animal uses

00:07:31.459 --> 00:07:33.910
the body in the environment.

00:07:33.910 --> 00:07:36.080
And I gave you the example
of the duck-billed platypus

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:38.060
because it's an extraordinary example

00:07:38.060 --> 00:07:39.188
of cortical magnification.

00:07:39.188 --> 00:07:41.260
But we must appreciate that we see this

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:42.900
across the board in a lot of species,

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:43.910
including humans.

00:07:43.910 --> 00:07:47.420
If you look at the evolution
of the supralaryngeal rack

00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:50.040
and the specializations
of this body morphology,

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:52.760
we have an expanded representation,

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:54.780
somatosensory cortex, motor
cortex, premotor cortex

00:07:54.780 --> 00:07:58.230
of this specialized structure
which we call Broca's Area.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:00.108
So they are following the same roles

00:08:00.108 --> 00:08:02.293
of evolution as other species.

00:08:03.220 --> 00:08:05.940
I'm gonna switch really rapidly

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:08.240
to experimental manipulations
of peripheral morphology.

00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:09.340
So you say, okay,

00:08:09.340 --> 00:08:12.900
to what extent is the ratio
of incoming sensory inputs

00:08:12.900 --> 00:08:14.741
to the developing neocortex

00:08:14.741 --> 00:08:17.490
determining the functional
organization of the neocortex?

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:18.323
And for this,

00:08:18.323 --> 00:08:19.630
we used little short-tailed opossums.

00:08:19.630 --> 00:08:21.142
They are models of early blindness.

00:08:21.142 --> 00:08:22.700
We bilaterally nucleated,

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:24.870
removed the eyes when
these animals are embryos.

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:26.570
So it's basically a little layer of skin.

00:08:26.570 --> 00:08:27.560
We let them grow up

00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:28.770
and we look at their connections,

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:31.220
we look at the functional
organization of their brain

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:33.870
and what we see is that
here's visual cortex

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:34.703
in this animal.

00:08:34.703 --> 00:08:35.536
This is the front of the brain

00:08:35.536 --> 00:08:36.369
and this is the top of the brain.

00:08:36.369 --> 00:08:38.620
And all of what would
normally be visual cortex,

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:39.790
which is in blue here,

00:08:39.790 --> 00:08:41.020
is now processing inputs

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:42.720
from the somatosensory
and auditory system.

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.020
So we've totally functionally

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:45.888
changed the reorganization
of this neocortex.

00:08:45.888 --> 00:08:49.010
And if we look at the connections,

00:08:49.010 --> 00:08:49.879
these are connections,

00:08:49.879 --> 00:08:52.218
these are visual areas here in blue,

00:08:52.218 --> 00:08:53.377
primary visual cortex

00:08:53.377 --> 00:08:55.800
and it's getting input from
other visual structures.

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.800
These are auditory structures in yellow

00:08:57.800 --> 00:08:59.710
and somatosensory structures in red.

00:08:59.710 --> 00:09:01.900
And what we see in our bilateral nucleus

00:09:01.900 --> 00:09:04.040
is that now the connections
of the brain have changed.

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:05.650
We've done nothing to
the neocortex itself,

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:06.550
not one thing.

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:08.670
We've simply removed all visual input

00:09:08.670 --> 00:09:09.960
really early in development.

00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:12.210
And what we see is this
functional takeover

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:14.680
and connectional takeover
of the developing brain.

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:18.379
And if we look at what that
region is representing,

00:09:18.379 --> 00:09:20.370
which would normally be visual,

00:09:20.370 --> 00:09:22.380
it's representing the head vibracy.

00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:23.410
We've basically,

00:09:23.410 --> 00:09:25.000
I want to say we've
made a platypus, right?

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:27.140
So something like 80% of the neocortex

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:29.450
is now processing inputs from this stuff,

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:31.653
from the vibracy and
the snout and the face.

00:09:32.923 --> 00:09:35.908
And of course, it's
great to have a big brain

00:09:35.908 --> 00:09:37.630
and transform the neocortex

00:09:37.630 --> 00:09:38.660
but you have to ask yourself

00:09:38.660 --> 00:09:39.900
what does this mean for behavior?

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:41.260
Which is the target of selection.

00:09:41.260 --> 00:09:43.360
And so we had train discrimination tasks

00:09:43.360 --> 00:09:44.240
and natural behavior.

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:45.550
And I wanted to show
you the natural behavior

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:46.750
'cause it's really cool.

00:09:47.630 --> 00:09:48.526
These animals,

00:09:48.526 --> 00:09:51.530
they end up becoming
super tactile animals.

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:52.470
They do really, really well

00:09:52.470 --> 00:09:53.645
with tactile discrimination tasks.

00:09:53.645 --> 00:09:55.130
This is the ladder rung task

00:09:55.130 --> 00:09:57.070
where the animal starts at one end

00:09:57.070 --> 00:09:59.030
of this ladder and moves to the other end

00:09:59.030 --> 00:10:02.290
and you train him to walk
on evenly spaced rungs.

00:10:02.290 --> 00:10:06.820
And then what you do is you
then space the rungs unevenly

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:08.150
and you have him do this task again.

00:10:08.150 --> 00:10:09.460
And I'm gonna show you
some movies of this.

00:10:09.460 --> 00:10:10.310
This is a normal animal,

00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:11.339
this is a bilateral nucleate

00:10:11.339 --> 00:10:13.770
and this is really pretty beautiful.

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:15.770
So here's what a normal animal looks like

00:10:15.770 --> 00:10:18.890
and you can score them based
on when their legs fall through

00:10:18.890 --> 00:10:19.723
and how well they do.

00:10:19.723 --> 00:10:20.760
You'll see this

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:25.760
and his legs falling
through, oops, oops, oops.

00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:29.500
He was trained but this
is now a novel task.

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:30.629
Here's the bilateral nucleate,

00:10:30.629 --> 00:10:32.530
no eyes whatsoever.

