00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:15.780
This is an injection site

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:17.020
and these are connections to it.

00:12:17.020 --> 00:12:18.960
But we also see
differences in connections.

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:20.290
And remember this is pretty subtle.

00:12:20.290 --> 00:12:21.540
And differences in connections

00:12:21.540 --> 00:12:22.782
of frontal cortex as well.

00:12:22.782 --> 00:12:24.920
So what factors contribute
to the phenotype?

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:27.480
So I'm just showing you a
much more subtle example

00:12:29.158 --> 00:12:30.750
of the role of sensory input

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:31.600
in shaping the brain,

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:32.543
in shaping connectivity.

00:12:32.543 --> 00:12:34.220
Well genes definitely contribute

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:37.360
to cortical sheet size,
cortical field size,

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:39.324
cortical connections,
peripheral morphology

00:12:39.324 --> 00:12:42.300
and cellular mechanisms
involved in plasticity,

00:12:42.300 --> 00:12:43.622
maybe genetically specified

00:12:43.622 --> 00:12:45.398
which allows the environment to impact

00:12:45.398 --> 00:12:47.250
some of these same things.

00:12:47.250 --> 00:12:49.480
I can change cortical field
size, cortical connectivity,

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:50.480
peripheral morphology,

00:12:50.480 --> 00:12:51.732
which I showed in these experiments.

00:12:51.732 --> 00:12:54.055
And I've given you examples
from the bill of the platypus

00:12:54.055 --> 00:12:57.377
and I suggested the same
thing is occurring in humans

00:12:57.377 --> 00:12:59.280
but what about things
like social learning,

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:00.363
language and culture?

00:13:01.330 --> 00:13:02.530
I would suggest

00:13:02.530 --> 00:13:03.856
that the best way to think about these

00:13:03.856 --> 00:13:07.015
as these are simply complex
patterns of physical stimuli

00:13:07.015 --> 00:13:09.680
that are impinging on the
developing nervous system.

00:13:09.680 --> 00:13:13.080
So mothers love is temperature, touch,

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:15.210
cadence of a voice, nothing more.

00:13:15.210 --> 00:13:19.420
And this can impact how
the brain wires itself.

00:13:19.420 --> 00:13:21.120
It can impact size of cortical fields

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:22.418
and connections of cortical fields.

00:13:22.418 --> 00:13:24.031
So I'm gonna end a little bit with this.

00:13:24.031 --> 00:13:26.641
This is a human evolution,

00:13:26.641 --> 00:13:28.420
not quite a cladogram.

00:13:28.420 --> 00:13:30.510
And on the bottom is
environment and social context

00:13:30.510 --> 00:13:33.295
and on the top it's
sort of truncated here,

00:13:33.295 --> 00:13:37.480
is meant to be morphology or genes.

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:40.060
And modern hand is proposed
to have been around this

00:13:40.060 --> 00:13:41.183
for about 700,000 years

00:13:41.183 --> 00:13:43.106
but what's really pretty fascinating

00:13:43.106 --> 00:13:47.208
is that until recently,
we were using stone tools.

00:13:47.208 --> 00:13:50.010
And big brains happened way back here.

00:13:50.010 --> 00:13:51.480
So we had the big brain,

00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:52.590
we had the modern hand

00:13:52.590 --> 00:13:54.200
but we were not doing what we're doing

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:55.060
with the modern hand.

00:13:55.060 --> 00:13:56.840
And if you believe that all behaviors

00:13:56.840 --> 00:13:57.840
is generated by the brain,

00:13:57.840 --> 00:14:00.000
and I believe that all behavior
is generated by the brain,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:01.500
then the brain must've changed.

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:02.710
And if the brain didn't change

00:14:02.710 --> 00:14:03.790
by changes in DNA sequence,

00:14:03.790 --> 00:14:06.252
it must've changed by
activity-dependent mechanisms

00:14:06.252 --> 00:14:07.680
and/or culture.

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:11.100
And so, it's hard to believe

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:12.070
that the industrial revolution

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:13.830
was less than 300 years ago.

00:14:13.830 --> 00:14:14.663
And if you look,

00:14:14.663 --> 00:14:16.500
we've actually changed
the scape of this planet

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:18.880
and now we have daily and
prolonged interactions

00:14:18.880 --> 00:14:21.070
with computers and machines and tools,

00:14:21.070 --> 00:14:22.430
really sophisticated tools.

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:23.539
And I'll end by saying

00:14:23.539 --> 00:14:25.250
we are combinatorial creatures

00:14:25.250 --> 00:14:27.230
constructed by genes, bodies, behaviors

00:14:27.230 --> 00:14:28.330
and environmental context

00:14:28.330 --> 00:14:30.288
and I think, you can look for the genes

00:14:30.288 --> 00:14:32.270
that are distinguishing humans,

00:14:32.270 --> 00:14:33.870
I think you're gonna find only a few,

00:14:33.870 --> 00:14:34.703
maybe some involved

00:14:34.703 --> 00:14:36.195
in expansion of the neocortex.

00:14:36.195 --> 00:14:37.423
But humans that have evolved

00:14:37.423 --> 00:14:40.023
an extraordinary capacity
to construct our neocortex

00:14:40.887 --> 00:14:42.900
over the course of a prolonged infancy

00:14:42.900 --> 00:14:45.187
and childhood allowing for
rapid phenotypic change

00:14:45.187 --> 00:14:46.930
even within a single generation.

00:14:46.930 --> 00:14:49.738
I would say that if Leah
Krubitzer were born 30 years ago

00:14:49.738 --> 00:14:53.750
or 100 years ago or 300,000 years ago,

00:14:53.750 --> 00:14:54.936
I wouldn't be Leah Krubitzer

00:14:54.936 --> 00:14:57.910
hitting a rock or using a spear,

00:14:57.910 --> 00:14:59.126
I would be a different brain.

00:14:59.126 --> 00:15:01.670
We have a remarkable
fluid brain body interface

00:15:01.670 --> 00:15:02.503
with the environment

00:15:02.503 --> 00:15:05.370
such that tools and machines
can extend our embodiment

00:15:05.370 --> 00:15:07.000
and our peri personal space

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:08.450
and expand the loop between our brains,

00:15:08.450 --> 00:15:09.590
our bodies and the world.

00:15:09.590 --> 00:15:13.000
And I think this has made us
unique biohybrid creatures

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.840
who's brains adapt and
bootstrap themselves

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:17.390
with the technologies that we give rise to

00:15:17.390 --> 00:15:18.810
and for better or worse,

00:15:18.810 --> 00:15:21.021
with whom are futures are
increasingly entwined.

00:15:21.021 --> 00:15:22.380
Okay, thank you.

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:25.380
(audience applause)

00:15:27.894 --> 00:15:29.462
- Paleoanthropologists once thought

00:15:29.462 --> 00:15:31.650
humans evolved in Europe and Asia

00:15:31.650 --> 00:15:33.629
around 40 to 50,000 years ago.

00:15:33.629 --> 00:15:36.890
We now know homo sapiens evolved in Africa

00:15:37.829 --> 00:15:40.850
more than 100 to 300,000 years ago.

00:15:40.850 --> 00:15:44.088
The evidence showing these earlier humans

00:15:44.088 --> 00:15:46.740
behaved in similar ways to recent humans

00:15:46.740 --> 00:15:48.228
continues to surprise us.

00:15:48.228 --> 00:15:49.533
But should it?

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:53.040
Here's an example.

00:15:53.040 --> 00:15:54.254
Several weeks ago,

00:15:54.254 --> 00:15:56.750
there was an article published in Nature,

00:15:56.750 --> 00:15:59.640
an abstract drawing from
the 73,000 year old levels

00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:01.780
at Blombos Cave in South Africa.

00:16:01.780 --> 00:16:03.706
Now this is an important discovery

00:16:03.706 --> 00:16:06.810
and it's published in one
of the world's foremost

00:16:06.810 --> 00:16:08.339
and prestigious scientific journals

00:16:08.339 --> 00:16:11.880
but abstract drawings are
human cultural universals.

00:16:11.880 --> 00:16:13.930
You're looking at some of them right now.

00:16:15.020 --> 00:16:16.173
Everyone makes them.

00:16:17.350 --> 00:16:18.300
Shouldn't we expect

00:16:18.300 --> 00:16:21.430
that humans who lived in
South Africa 73,000 years ago

00:16:21.430 --> 00:16:23.299
made abstract drawings too?

00:16:23.299 --> 00:16:27.697
Are early humans not
behavioring modern humans?

00:16:27.697 --> 00:16:29.393
Were they these primitive humans

00:16:29.393 --> 00:16:32.145
that anthropologists have been
looking for and not finding

00:16:32.145 --> 00:16:33.943
for more than two centuries?

00:16:35.703 --> 00:16:37.429
I think we have to ask

00:16:37.429 --> 00:16:39.580
what is behavioral modernity

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:41.084
and take a closer look at it.

00:16:41.084 --> 00:16:42.714
It's inferred quality

00:16:42.714 --> 00:16:46.080
based on unexpected
archeological discoveries,

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:49.330
art, symbols, carved bone
tools and similar things

00:16:49.330 --> 00:16:53.650
rather than things predicted
from prior evolutionary theory

00:16:53.650 --> 00:16:55.553
before the excavations started.

00:16:56.660 --> 00:16:59.180
Modernity claims come first,

00:16:59.180 --> 00:17:00.710
supporting evidence, arguments

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:02.533
and theoretical justifications

00:17:02.533 --> 00:17:04.924
are developed after the fact.

00:17:04.924 --> 00:17:07.100
This is not a good way to do science

00:17:07.100 --> 00:17:09.860
and it is a demonstrably
poor way to do justice

00:17:09.860 --> 00:17:13.080
because long ago, people
in Salem, Massachusetts

00:17:13.080 --> 00:17:15.473
used this same approach
to identify witches.

00:17:18.070 --> 00:17:20.094
Witchcraft accusations came first.

00:17:20.094 --> 00:17:21.487
Evidence was then gathered

00:17:21.487 --> 00:17:23.812
and theories developed after the fact.

00:17:23.812 --> 00:17:25.929
More than 200 people were accused,

00:17:25.929 --> 00:17:27.710
dozens jailed.

00:17:27.710 --> 00:17:30.490
19 hanged and one tortured to death.

00:17:30.490 --> 00:17:32.770
And yet Massachusetts exonerated

00:17:32.770 --> 00:17:37.133
most accused and convicted
witches 17 years later in 1703.

00:17:37.987 --> 00:17:40.000
Why should we expect our search

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.040
for prehistoric behaviorally modern humans

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:43.866
to be any more successful and enduring

00:17:43.866 --> 00:17:47.029
than Salem's search for witches?

00:17:47.029 --> 00:17:49.002
I don't think we should.

00:17:49.002 --> 00:17:52.040
So what's wrong with behavioral modernity?

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:53.988
First off, it's anti-evolutionary.

00:17:53.988 --> 00:17:56.604
It assumes all humans evolved convergently

00:17:56.604 --> 00:17:57.655
towards the same end

00:17:57.655 --> 00:18:01.239
and regardless of divergent
selective pressures.

00:18:01.239 --> 00:18:03.295
Secondly, it's a metaphor

00:18:03.295 --> 00:18:06.790
rather than measurable
property of the evidence.

00:18:06.790 --> 00:18:10.646
And a metaphor that
archeologists choose selectively.

00:18:10.646 --> 00:18:11.940
It doesn't predict.

00:18:11.940 --> 00:18:13.880
All of its interpretations

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:15.910
are made after the fact.

00:18:15.910 --> 00:18:16.989
I think it's better to focus,

00:18:16.989 --> 00:18:17.900
and I'll propose,

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:21.410
it's better to focus on
behavioral complexity instead.

00:18:21.410 --> 00:18:22.439
With behavioral modernity,

00:18:22.439 --> 00:18:23.850
different lightning bolts

00:18:23.850 --> 00:18:26.160
will all produce the same
kinds of stone tools.

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:29.360
Don't nap outdoors
during a lightning storm.

00:18:29.360 --> 00:18:30.302
With behavioral complexity,

00:18:30.302 --> 00:18:33.344
different causes beget different results.

00:18:33.344 --> 00:18:37.147
So what is behavioral complexity?

00:18:37.147 --> 00:18:39.910
Well, key features of complex phenomena

00:18:39.910 --> 00:18:40.902
include multiple parts

00:18:40.902 --> 00:18:43.433
that interact with one
another systematically.

00:18:43.433 --> 00:18:47.485
Different inputs create different outputs.

00:18:47.485 --> 00:18:51.310
And historical and geographic
variation among inputs

00:18:51.310 --> 00:18:53.720
creates complexly-patterned variability

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:55.110
among the outputs.

00:18:55.110 --> 00:18:56.230
That whole system,

00:18:56.230 --> 00:18:57.160
too much systems theory.

00:18:57.160 --> 00:18:58.286
Here's a practical example.

00:18:58.286 --> 00:19:00.840
Folk art is a complex phenomenon

00:19:00.840 --> 00:19:03.370
in which artists, cultures,
materials and markets

00:19:03.370 --> 00:19:05.250
interact dynamically with one another.

00:19:05.250 --> 00:19:06.832
If you think folk art is simple

00:19:06.832 --> 00:19:09.930
do please join us in Santa Fe, New Mexico

00:19:09.930 --> 00:19:12.400
for the International Folk Art Festival

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:14.220
that happens each July.

00:19:14.220 --> 00:19:18.370
Handcrafted artifacts vary
historically and geographically

00:19:18.370 --> 00:19:20.233
in complexly patterned ways.

00:19:21.807 --> 00:19:26.140
So how complex was early
human stone working?

00:19:26.140 --> 00:19:28.750
Today, stone working or making stone tools

00:19:28.750 --> 00:19:30.710
is a handy craft, a folk art,

00:19:30.710 --> 00:19:32.253
of which I'm a practitioner.

00:19:34.103 --> 00:19:35.980
It's also a reasonable
source of hypotheses

00:19:35.980 --> 00:19:38.560
about prehistoric stoneworking

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:41.143
because it's familiar, we can observe it.

00:19:41.143 --> 00:19:44.110
If early Homo sapiens
had similar capacities

00:19:44.110 --> 00:19:46.216
for behavioral variability,

00:19:46.216 --> 00:19:50.100
excuse me, for behavioral
complexity to ours

00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:52.450
and different ones from earlier hominins,

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:55.190
then their first appearances
in the fossil record

00:19:55.190 --> 00:19:59.000
should coincide with onsets
of complexly patterned

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:00.600
stone tool variability.

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:01.680
Here's a prediction.

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:02.820
Does it?

00:20:02.820 --> 00:20:03.980
Well indeed it does.

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:06.540
After 100 to 300,000 years ago,

00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:08.802
Homo sapiens first appearances everywhere

00:20:08.802 --> 00:20:12.394
coincide with increasingly
complex and patterned

00:20:12.394 --> 00:20:14.820
stone tool variability.

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:18.303
So what is complexly patterned
stone tool variability?

