00:21:33.630 --> 00:21:36.414
the one with the hollow sort of base,

00:21:36.414 --> 00:21:39.394
that's an artifact found
here in North America

00:21:39.394 --> 00:21:43.260
but from the Mississippi
River to the Rocky Mountains

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:44.550
and up to the Great Plains

00:21:44.550 --> 00:21:47.100
over the course of about two centuries.

00:21:47.100 --> 00:21:48.798
Excuse me, 2,000 years.

00:21:48.798 --> 00:21:51.750
What do stone tools teach us?

00:21:51.750 --> 00:21:55.220
First off, stone tools are
indestructible evidence

00:21:55.220 --> 00:21:58.003
about mind-technology relationships.

00:21:59.810 --> 00:22:03.860
This evidence shows complex
mind-technology relationships

00:22:03.860 --> 00:22:05.670
were in place among early humans

00:22:05.670 --> 00:22:08.533
at least 100 to 300,000 years ago.

00:22:09.820 --> 00:22:11.740
Increasingly complex stone tool

00:22:11.740 --> 00:22:13.070
and other artifact variability

00:22:13.070 --> 00:22:15.260
since 100,000 years ago

00:22:15.260 --> 00:22:18.382
suggests mind-technology
relationships changed

00:22:18.382 --> 00:22:20.810
during the course of human evolution.

00:22:20.810 --> 00:22:22.010
So if we're trying to discover

00:22:22.010 --> 00:22:24.630
the influence of the mind on technology

00:22:24.630 --> 00:22:26.220
and technology on the mind,

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:28.920
we need to remember we're
shooting at a moving target.

00:22:31.930 --> 00:22:34.170
So why?

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:35.350
These are the fun questions.

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:37.390
Why does stone tool variability

00:22:37.390 --> 00:22:40.130
become increasingly complex and patterned?

00:22:40.130 --> 00:22:42.177
Tools can be evolutionarily advantageous

00:22:42.177 --> 00:22:46.163
but they come with costs
few other animals tolerate.

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:50.570
Other primates occasionally use tools

00:22:50.570 --> 00:22:54.981
but only Homo sapiens are
obligatory tool users.

00:22:54.981 --> 00:22:58.360
Obligatory tool use is irreversible,

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:01.910
even the best survival
experts require tools.

00:23:01.910 --> 00:23:03.730
How many of you guys will
fess up to seeing this show,

00:23:03.730 --> 00:23:04.658
Naked and Afraid?

00:23:04.658 --> 00:23:07.890
Come on, you've seen this.

00:23:07.890 --> 00:23:09.410
I know at least one other
of you in the audience

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:12.190
has been like me, recruited
to participate in it.

00:23:12.190 --> 00:23:13.220
I don't want to treat my students

00:23:13.220 --> 00:23:15.570
to pictures of me running
around without clothes.

00:23:15.570 --> 00:23:17.900
They couldn't get
insurance for this program

00:23:17.900 --> 00:23:20.300
unless they equipped the
contestants with tools.

00:23:21.460 --> 00:23:22.917
It wouldn't be called Naked and Afraid,

00:23:22.917 --> 00:23:24.617
it would be called Naked and Dead.

00:23:26.830 --> 00:23:31.150
Now as I say, it's irreversible,

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:33.350
we can't go back.

00:23:33.350 --> 00:23:36.370
More tool use increases
cultural differences potential,

00:23:36.370 --> 00:23:38.580
influence on tool making strategies.

00:23:38.580 --> 00:23:41.723
I like to call this the no,
you're doing it wrong effect.

00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:44.427
So what do we know,

00:23:44.427 --> 00:23:45.761
what do we not know

00:23:45.761 --> 00:23:47.393
and what do we want to know?

00:23:48.230 --> 00:23:49.630
We know obligatory tool use

00:23:49.630 --> 00:23:51.950
is intrinsically complex and variable

00:23:51.950 --> 00:23:54.530
and these are quantities we can measure

00:23:54.530 --> 00:23:56.960
using the stone tool evidence.

00:23:56.960 --> 00:23:58.248
We do not know

00:23:58.248 --> 00:24:00.105
whether obligatory tool use

00:24:00.105 --> 00:24:02.140
was a uniquely derived characteristic

00:24:02.140 --> 00:24:03.710
of Homo sapien's behavior

00:24:03.710 --> 00:24:07.540
or one shared by other
hominins now extinct,

00:24:07.540 --> 00:24:09.883
such as denisovans and
neanderthals, perhaps.

00:24:12.630 --> 00:24:14.680
We find ourselves in a happy spot

00:24:14.680 --> 00:24:16.610
where we have new research questions.

00:24:16.610 --> 00:24:18.330
You always want to come up
with new research questions.

00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:20.210
You don't want to just hang up your spears

00:24:20.210 --> 00:24:23.092
and go do something else.

00:24:23.092 --> 00:24:26.250
How did obligatory tool
use change the human mind

00:24:26.250 --> 00:24:29.398
from earlier primate
and hominin conditions?

00:24:29.398 --> 00:24:32.593
And how do we didect obligatory tool use?

00:24:33.460 --> 00:24:35.250
Now some of my colleagues might say,

00:24:35.250 --> 00:24:36.906
and I'm not referring
to anyone in the room,

00:24:36.906 --> 00:24:38.250
some of my colleagues might say

00:24:38.250 --> 00:24:42.170
we have an arsenal of ways
of measuring stone tools

00:24:42.170 --> 00:24:43.580
and quantifying their variability

00:24:43.580 --> 00:24:46.516
that we've been using for 200 years.

00:24:46.516 --> 00:24:47.940
But archeologists

00:24:47.940 --> 00:24:50.741
who formulated those
measurements 200 years ago

00:24:50.741 --> 00:24:54.590
weren't thinking about
obligatory tool use.

00:24:54.590 --> 00:24:55.860
So we're in a situation

00:24:55.860 --> 00:24:58.320
where we have a tool box
full of hammers and chisels

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:02.650
and we're setting forth
to change the battery

00:25:02.650 --> 00:25:04.330
on an iPhone.

00:25:04.330 --> 00:25:06.480
So I don't think the existing tools

00:25:06.480 --> 00:25:08.925
archeologists used to
characterize the stone tool record

00:25:08.925 --> 00:25:12.480
are necessarily unhelpful

00:25:12.480 --> 00:25:14.622
but we have to prove that value.

00:25:14.622 --> 00:25:16.096
Thank you.

00:25:16.096 --> 00:25:19.096
