00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:39.870
Language coevolved with the human brain

00:25:39.870 --> 00:25:43.470
throughout evolution of Homo sapiens.

00:25:43.470 --> 00:25:45.300
Writing, on the other hand,

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:47.670
which is actually what my topic is,

00:25:47.670 --> 00:25:50.630
is a relatively new technology

00:25:50.630 --> 00:25:52.190
that was invented by humans

00:25:52.190 --> 00:25:56.018
to translate spoken
language into a visual form

00:25:56.018 --> 00:26:00.006
for the purpose of transmitting
verbal communication

00:26:00.006 --> 00:26:05.006
broadly to many people over
large distances and time.

00:26:06.130 --> 00:26:08.530
As such, reading and writing

00:26:08.530 --> 00:26:11.513
can be considered the first social media.

00:26:13.995 --> 00:26:18.300
Reading is an example of what's
called neuronal recycling,

00:26:18.300 --> 00:26:21.299
the recruitment of previously
evolved neural circuits

00:26:21.299 --> 00:26:24.821
to accomplish cultural innovations.

00:26:24.821 --> 00:26:26.870
It's important to point out

00:26:26.870 --> 00:26:30.390
that while language develops
naturally in most humans

00:26:30.390 --> 00:26:34.449
based on exposure rather
than explicit instruction,

00:26:34.449 --> 00:26:37.890
reading and writing require
painstaking instruction

00:26:37.890 --> 00:26:41.370
and years of practice
to reach proficiency.

00:26:41.370 --> 00:26:44.016
This slide shows the typical
reading brain network

00:26:44.016 --> 00:26:45.774
with its key components

00:26:45.774 --> 00:26:49.380
as established initially in an older view

00:26:49.380 --> 00:26:53.230
by studies of patients with
acquired brain lesions.

00:26:53.230 --> 00:26:57.070
And more recently, using modern
brain imaging technologies,

00:26:57.070 --> 00:26:58.833
we have a lot more information.

00:27:01.650 --> 00:27:03.940
This talk will trace the history

00:27:03.940 --> 00:27:06.663
of the invention of writing,

00:27:09.266 --> 00:27:12.280
how English writing developed

00:27:12.280 --> 00:27:16.270
and ended up with such a
cockeyed spelling system

00:27:16.270 --> 00:27:19.013
which leads in many cases to dyslexia,

00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:22.470
and discuss how modern technologies

00:27:22.470 --> 00:27:25.303
are impacting reading and writing today.

00:27:26.610 --> 00:27:28.600
I'd like to begin with a brief overview

00:27:28.600 --> 00:27:31.563
of the history of the
invention of writing.

00:27:33.156 --> 00:27:35.820
Writing is a physical manifestation

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:37.920
of a spoken language.

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:40.820
It's thought that human beings
developed spoken language

00:27:40.820 --> 00:27:43.878
about 35,000 BC

00:27:43.878 --> 00:27:48.350
as evidenced by, wow
yeah, by cave paintings

00:27:48.350 --> 00:27:51.150
from the period of cro magnum man.

00:27:51.150 --> 00:27:53.520
Writing numbers for the
purpose of record keeping

00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:57.101
began long before writing of language.

00:27:57.101 --> 00:27:59.029
Written language doesn't emerge

00:27:59.029 --> 00:28:03.100
until the invention in Sumer
in southern Mesopotamia

00:28:03.100 --> 00:28:06.650
around 3,500 BC.

00:28:06.650 --> 00:28:10.581
This writing system is
known as Cuneiform writing.

00:28:10.581 --> 00:28:14.220
It's generally agreed that
true writing of language

00:28:14.220 --> 00:28:17.140
was independently conceived and developed

00:28:17.140 --> 00:28:21.170
by at least two ancient
civilizations and possibly more.

00:28:21.170 --> 00:28:25.230
In Sumer and also in
Mesoamerica by the Maya

00:28:25.230 --> 00:28:27.633
in 500 to 300 BC.

00:28:28.610 --> 00:28:33.100
Writing systems also arose
in Egypt around 3100 BC

00:28:33.100 --> 00:28:36.237
and China around 1200 BC.

00:28:36.237 --> 00:28:38.170
But historians debate

00:28:38.170 --> 00:28:39.500
whether these writing systems

00:28:39.500 --> 00:28:42.666
were developed completely
independently of Sumerian writing

00:28:42.666 --> 00:28:46.810
or whether either or both were
inspired by Sumerian writing

00:28:46.810 --> 00:28:49.163
by a process of cultural diffusion.

00:28:50.343 --> 00:28:53.430
The Sumerian Cuneiform writing system

00:28:53.430 --> 00:28:55.950
was in use for more than three millennia

00:28:55.950 --> 00:28:57.870
through several stages of development

00:28:57.870 --> 00:28:59.860
as can be seen on this slide

00:28:59.860 --> 00:29:02.317
by looking at the
transformation of the sign

00:29:02.317 --> 00:29:04.620
for head SAG

00:29:04.620 --> 00:29:08.710
beginning with pictograms in 3000 BC.

00:29:08.710 --> 00:29:10.700
Ultimately it was completely replaced

00:29:10.700 --> 00:29:13.358
by alphabetic writing
in the general sense.

00:29:13.358 --> 00:29:15.797
In the course of the Roman era,

00:29:15.797 --> 00:29:20.163
there are no Cuneiform
writing systems in use today.

00:29:21.343 --> 00:29:24.450
While the development
of Phoenician alphabet

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:26.701
is often attributed to,

00:29:26.701 --> 00:29:30.320
the Phonetic alphabet is
also often contributed

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:31.510
to the Phoenicians,

00:29:31.510 --> 00:29:34.770
they didn't actually
invent it or create it.

00:29:34.770 --> 00:29:37.960
Rather, they imported it
piecemeal from Egypt and Crete

00:29:37.960 --> 00:29:41.670
and took it to every city
on the Mediterranean.

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:42.910
By the time of Homer,

00:29:42.910 --> 00:29:45.060
the Greeks were taking over the Phoenician

00:29:45.060 --> 00:29:48.000
or allied Aramaic, alphabetic writing

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.190
and were calling it by the Semitic names

00:29:50.190 --> 00:29:53.600
of the first two letters, alpha and beta.

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:55.240
The Latin alphabet was established

00:29:55.240 --> 00:29:57.633
by the seventh century BC.

00:29:58.814 --> 00:30:01.620
Before the invention of the
printing press in Europe

00:30:01.620 --> 00:30:03.400
around 1455,

00:30:03.400 --> 00:30:06.710
all books were handwritten
and usually highly decorated

00:30:06.710 --> 00:30:08.290
until about the 12th century,

00:30:08.290 --> 00:30:10.491
the most elaborate and
beautiful illuminations

00:30:10.491 --> 00:30:12.660
were devoted to religious works

00:30:12.660 --> 00:30:16.370
and most manuscripts were
produced in monasteries.

00:30:16.370 --> 00:30:17.440
During the middle ages,

00:30:17.440 --> 00:30:19.650
the Latin alphabet was used extensively

00:30:19.650 --> 00:30:21.211
for writing in Europe.

00:30:21.211 --> 00:30:23.200
With the age of colonialism

00:30:23.200 --> 00:30:24.781
and Christian evangelism

00:30:24.781 --> 00:30:28.883
the Latin scripts spread
widely well beyond Europe.

00:30:30.410 --> 00:30:33.380
I'd now like to change the focus

00:30:33.380 --> 00:30:36.120
to the history of English writing

00:30:36.120 --> 00:30:37.970
and explain how English writing

00:30:37.970 --> 00:30:40.600
ended up with such a
cockeyed spelling system

00:30:40.600 --> 00:30:42.893
which leads in many cases to dyslexia.

00:30:45.240 --> 00:30:47.150
The English language itself

00:30:47.150 --> 00:30:50.960
is a compilation of several
different languages,

00:30:50.960 --> 00:30:54.910
mostly Anglo-Saxon, French and Latin

00:30:54.910 --> 00:30:56.960
because England just kept getting invaded

00:30:56.960 --> 00:30:59.650
by people who spoke different languages.

00:30:59.650 --> 00:31:01.430
The only thing we have in English

00:31:01.430 --> 00:31:04.690
up until about 1400 are called patois.

00:31:04.690 --> 00:31:06.270
They're a clumsy peasant language

00:31:06.270 --> 00:31:09.690
without any standardized writing system.

00:31:09.690 --> 00:31:11.490
There wasn't even a vocabulary

00:31:11.490 --> 00:31:13.860
to carry on business in English.

00:31:13.860 --> 00:31:16.830
It was all done in French or Latin.

00:31:16.830 --> 00:31:19.610
However, when King Henry the Fifth

00:31:19.610 --> 00:31:22.120
took the throne of England in 1412,

00:31:22.120 --> 00:31:24.520
he had plans to invade France.

00:31:24.520 --> 00:31:26.770
So speaking French wasn't gonna work.

00:31:26.770 --> 00:31:29.046
He realized that if he
wanted to get support

00:31:29.046 --> 00:31:30.740
from the common people,

00:31:30.740 --> 00:31:32.850
they would have to change the language

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:36.853
of Parliament and business
from French to English.

00:31:38.434 --> 00:31:39.490
At this time,

00:31:39.490 --> 00:31:41.940
the only people who could
write at all in England

00:31:41.940 --> 00:31:45.310
were just a handful of men
called chancery scribes

00:31:45.310 --> 00:31:49.590
who wrote by hand and
almost exclusively in Latin.

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:53.650
Latin has a transparent
one to one correspondence

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:57.480
between the number of discrete
sounds, called phonemes,

00:31:57.480 --> 00:31:59.130
in spoken Latin

00:31:59.130 --> 00:32:03.150
and how they're mapped by
the letters in the alphabet.

00:32:03.150 --> 00:32:06.140
As such, learning to read
Latin's a piece of cake.

00:32:06.140 --> 00:32:08.258
All you have to do is
learn the single letter

00:32:08.258 --> 00:32:11.170
that goes with each phoneme in Latin

00:32:11.170 --> 00:32:13.140
and then just pronounce them in order

00:32:13.140 --> 00:32:14.413
to produce words.

00:32:15.761 --> 00:32:19.660
King Henry the Fifth
directed his chancery scribes

00:32:19.660 --> 00:32:22.260
to create a written version of English

00:32:22.260 --> 00:32:25.630
so that he could communicate
more broadly with his subjects.

00:32:25.630 --> 00:32:28.045
However, there was
little or no instruction

00:32:28.045 --> 00:32:31.170
as to how they were supposed to do this.

00:32:31.170 --> 00:32:34.300
The problem they faced was
that the written Latin alphabet

00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:36.700
was designed to represent one on one,

00:32:36.700 --> 00:32:40.710
each of the 23 phonemes in spoken Latin.

00:32:40.710 --> 00:32:42.840
It was never fit well for English

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:45.380
which has 44 phonemes.

00:32:45.380 --> 00:32:50.380
For example, Latin didn't
have a sh, th or ch sound.

00:32:51.602 --> 00:32:53.991
So with only 23 Latin letters,

00:32:53.991 --> 00:32:56.300
there was no letter to represent these

00:32:56.300 --> 00:33:00.110
and many of the other 44 English phonemes.

00:33:00.110 --> 00:33:01.310
Faced with this problem,

00:33:01.310 --> 00:33:03.550
the chancery scribes just apparently

00:33:03.550 --> 00:33:05.980
made up multi-letter combinations

00:33:05.980 --> 00:33:08.323
to represent these single phonemes.

00:33:09.658 --> 00:33:12.201
So for example on this slide,

00:33:12.201 --> 00:33:17.201
you could see that the letter string t-h-e

00:33:17.413 --> 00:33:20.887
pronounced phonetically should be te-hu-e

00:33:22.290 --> 00:33:26.700
and s-h-e, sa-hu-e.

00:33:26.700 --> 00:33:27.980
So as many children are told

00:33:27.980 --> 00:33:30.120
just say those and blend
the together quickly

00:33:30.120 --> 00:33:31.420
and what do you get?

00:33:31.420 --> 00:33:32.650
Sa-hu-e.

00:33:33.984 --> 00:33:37.260
(audience laughing)

00:33:37.260 --> 00:33:38.390
In case you ever wondered

00:33:38.390 --> 00:33:41.160
how we ended up with the
non-transparent mapping

00:33:41.160 --> 00:33:43.060
from spoken to written English

00:33:43.060 --> 00:33:44.980
that leads so many children and people

00:33:44.980 --> 00:33:47.160
learning English as a second language

00:33:47.160 --> 00:33:49.630
to struggle to learn to read and spell.

00:33:49.630 --> 00:33:52.590
It all began here in the 15th century.

00:33:52.590 --> 00:33:55.400
Nearly 600 years before Gutenberg,

00:33:55.400 --> 00:33:58.420
Chinese monks were setting ink to paper

00:33:58.420 --> 00:34:01.390
using a method known as block printing.

00:34:01.390 --> 00:34:03.880
What really set Gutenberg's
technology apart

00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:05.390
from the Chinese

00:34:05.390 --> 00:34:07.000
was the development of a press

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.420
that could mechanize the transfer of ink

00:34:09.420 --> 00:34:11.713
from movable type to paper.

00:34:12.580 --> 00:34:14.080
For the first time in history,

00:34:14.080 --> 00:34:16.234
books could be mass produced.

00:34:16.234 --> 00:34:20.450
Gutenberg's first major work in 1454

00:34:20.450 --> 00:34:25.450
was the 42 line Gutenberg
bible printed in Latin.

00:34:26.849 --> 00:34:29.150
With the invention of the printing press,

00:34:29.150 --> 00:34:33.020
printing soon became the first
means of mass communication,

00:34:33.020 --> 00:34:35.660
really the first social media.

00:34:35.660 --> 00:34:39.060
It put more knowledge in the
hands of more people faster

00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:42.380
and more cheaply than ever before.

00:34:42.380 --> 00:34:44.090
As a result, reading and writing,

00:34:44.090 --> 00:34:46.240
which up until that time
was really something

00:34:46.240 --> 00:34:49.150
done by a very, very
small number of people

00:34:49.150 --> 00:34:51.143
spread widely and rapidly.

00:34:52.409 --> 00:34:54.740
Caxton brought the first printing press

00:34:54.740 --> 00:34:59.740
from Bruges to London in 1476
for the Canterbury Tales.

00:35:00.540 --> 00:35:02.260
With the advent of the printing press,

00:35:02.260 --> 00:35:05.846
the complex and often cockeyed
spelling patterns for English

00:35:05.846 --> 00:35:10.000
that remain to this day were solidified

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.400
giving rise to generation after generation

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:13.490
of children and adults

00:35:13.490 --> 00:35:15.900
who struggled to learn to read and write,

00:35:15.900 --> 00:35:17.433
particularly in English.

