lot of this for this talk.

00:35:39.590 --> 00:35:42.340
I highly recommend that
you explore this website

00:35:42.340 --> 00:35:44.570
for additional information on this topic

00:35:44.570 --> 00:35:45.970
of reading and writing,

00:35:45.970 --> 00:35:47.300
the history of reading and writing

00:35:47.300 --> 00:35:49.461
and especially dyslexia.

00:35:49.461 --> 00:35:51.694
I quote from David Bolton,

00:35:51.694 --> 00:35:54.577
"There weren't any cognitive scientists

00:35:54.577 --> 00:35:56.727
"or neuroscientists or psychologists

00:35:56.727 --> 00:35:58.747
"or even child development experts

00:35:58.747 --> 00:36:01.583
"involved in creating the
English writing system.

00:36:03.127 --> 00:36:04.817
"There wasn't any concern

00:36:04.817 --> 00:36:06.577
"for hundreds of millions of children

00:36:06.577 --> 00:36:07.487
"who would struggle

00:36:07.487 --> 00:36:10.967
"since this code was
created in the 15th century.

00:36:10.967 --> 00:36:13.527
"There were just a small
number of chancery scribes

00:36:13.527 --> 00:36:14.847
"doing their very best

00:36:14.847 --> 00:36:17.637
"to shove a technology created for Latin

00:36:17.637 --> 00:36:21.747
"into a language it
was never designed for.

00:36:21.747 --> 00:36:24.913
"Those who eventually do manage
to overcome the confusion

00:36:24.913 --> 00:36:27.090
"and learn how to break the code,

00:36:27.090 --> 00:36:29.453
"to become phonologically aware

00:36:29.453 --> 00:36:32.147
"are able to use the areas of the brain

00:36:32.147 --> 00:36:35.308
"that reading has recycled
from speech and language."

00:36:35.308 --> 00:36:36.983
These areas here.

00:36:38.582 --> 00:36:42.997
"Those who cannot break
this code become dyslexic."

00:36:45.680 --> 00:36:48.330
According to the United
States Department of Education

00:36:48.330 --> 00:36:53.330
in 2017, more than 60% of US
K through 12 school children

00:36:54.100 --> 00:36:56.020
are reading below proficiency

00:36:56.020 --> 00:37:00.308
and more than 70% writing
below the level of proficiency

00:37:00.308 --> 00:37:02.960
for that grade level.

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:05.163
Let these stunning numbers sink in.

00:37:07.268 --> 00:37:11.590
Reading is the skill that
matters most to success in school

00:37:11.590 --> 00:37:14.130
and children who fall behind in reading

00:37:14.130 --> 00:37:16.760
are in great academic danger.

00:37:16.760 --> 00:37:19.340
But it's not just the
lack of reading skills

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:21.418
that most endanger these children.

00:37:21.418 --> 00:37:24.110
It's the collateral damage.

00:37:24.110 --> 00:37:28.330
It's their mind shame
that fates their future.

00:37:28.330 --> 00:37:30.280
As seen on this video clip being shown

00:37:30.280 --> 00:37:32.520
with permission of Children of the Code.

00:37:32.520 --> 00:37:35.570
- My teacher asked me to come
into the front of the class

00:37:35.570 --> 00:37:36.403
and read a book

00:37:36.403 --> 00:37:39.450
and everybody was just staring at me

00:37:39.450 --> 00:37:41.151
and I got real nervous

00:37:41.151 --> 00:37:43.126
'cause I didn't want
to mess up or anything.

00:37:43.126 --> 00:37:44.517
And then when I started reading,

00:37:44.517 --> 00:37:45.692
I started messing up

00:37:45.692 --> 00:37:47.950
and I just couldn't help it

00:37:47.950 --> 00:37:49.930
and everybody started
laughing at me and stuff.

00:37:49.930 --> 00:37:52.320
- Like the teacher would
ask me to read something

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:54.760
and I would read it and
I'd get a wrong word

00:37:54.760 --> 00:37:56.946
or I'd go too slow and
they'll make fun of me.

00:37:56.946 --> 00:37:58.660
- I kept messing up on the words

00:37:58.660 --> 00:38:00.210
and people kept laughing at me.

00:38:01.389 --> 00:38:03.750
- They said that you
don't know how to read,

00:38:03.750 --> 00:38:08.750
I bet you won't be able to
how to read when you grow up.

00:38:10.944 --> 00:38:15.897
- They always laugh at me if
I get twist up with words.

00:38:15.897 --> 00:38:18.796
It makes my heart drop

00:38:18.796 --> 00:38:21.653
'cause it seem like they
not my friend no more.

00:38:22.692 --> 00:38:25.920
- The collateral damage
caused by literacy problems

00:38:25.920 --> 00:38:28.962
in the United States alone is immense.

00:38:28.962 --> 00:38:33.962
75% to 80% of students
identified as learning disabled

00:38:34.404 --> 00:38:38.680
have their basic deficits
in language and reading.

00:38:38.680 --> 00:38:39.968
Academic success,

00:38:39.968 --> 00:38:43.610
as defined by high school graduation,

00:38:43.610 --> 00:38:46.650
can be predicted by knowing
someone's reading skill

00:38:46.650 --> 00:38:49.185
at the end of third grade.

00:38:49.185 --> 00:38:52.250
56% of students with learning disabilities

00:38:52.250 --> 00:38:54.913
will drop out of school and be arrested.

00:38:56.488 --> 00:39:00.570
60% of adolescents in
treatment for substance abuse

00:39:00.570 --> 00:39:02.143
have learning disabilities.

00:39:03.434 --> 00:39:08.090
50% of females with learning
disabilities will be mothers,

00:39:08.090 --> 00:39:09.740
many of them single mothers,

00:39:09.740 --> 00:39:13.223
within three to five years
of leaving high school.

00:39:14.490 --> 00:39:17.357
Learning disabilities and substance abuse

00:39:17.357 --> 00:39:22.357
are the number one reason for
keeping welfare recipients

00:39:23.030 --> 00:39:26.023
from becoming and remaining employed.

00:39:28.729 --> 00:39:31.120
Now I'm gonna turn to discussing

00:39:31.120 --> 00:39:34.170
how modern technologies
are impacting reading

00:39:34.170 --> 00:39:35.503
and writing today.

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:42.490
Lest we forget,

00:39:42.490 --> 00:39:46.730
the human brain is an
exquisitely adaptable machine.

00:39:46.730 --> 00:39:48.180
Even though written language

00:39:48.180 --> 00:39:50.290
did not evolve like spoken language did

00:39:50.290 --> 00:39:52.550
over tens of millions of years ago,

00:39:52.550 --> 00:39:55.340
since the invention of
writing and reading,

00:39:55.340 --> 00:39:58.370
the remarkable neuroplasticity
of the human brain

00:39:58.370 --> 00:40:00.720
has supported the rapid formation

00:40:00.720 --> 00:40:05.430
of a highly elaborate
literacy brain circuit.

00:40:05.430 --> 00:40:10.220
Literacy is a unique
epigenetic achievement

00:40:10.220 --> 00:40:12.279
that changes what we perceive,

00:40:12.279 --> 00:40:15.510
how we think and how we feel,

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:18.140
that is who we are.

00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:20.560
I think it's fair to say
that reading and writing,

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:23.260
perhaps more than any other technology

00:40:23.260 --> 00:40:24.950
have had the greatest impact

00:40:24.950 --> 00:40:29.035
on the advancement of Homo
sapien brain and mind.

00:40:29.035 --> 00:40:31.761
As we gain proficiency
in reading and writing,

00:40:31.761 --> 00:40:35.469
the continual use of our
literacy brain circuit

00:40:35.469 --> 00:40:39.693
feeds back, elaborates
and strengthens itself.

00:40:39.693 --> 00:40:43.199
But just as this brain
circuit developed very rapidly

00:40:43.199 --> 00:40:45.083
in evolutionary terms

00:40:45.083 --> 00:40:50.083
or perhaps because it was so rapid,

00:40:50.630 --> 00:40:55.150
this circuit is also more
vulnerable to change,

00:40:55.150 --> 00:40:59.733
if not continuously reinforced
by experience and use.

00:41:01.368 --> 00:41:04.020
Only if we continuously work

00:41:04.020 --> 00:41:07.440
to develop and use the
elaborated, analytical,

00:41:07.440 --> 00:41:09.987
inferential and empathetic skills

00:41:09.987 --> 00:41:12.570
that have been developed by literacy

00:41:12.570 --> 00:41:15.150
will the neural networks
underlying these skills

00:41:15.150 --> 00:41:19.930
continue to sustain our
capacity to be attentive,

00:41:19.930 --> 00:41:22.360
thoughtful, critical thinkers

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:27.360
rather than passive consumers
of facts, real or fake.

00:41:31.460 --> 00:41:32.810
Despite alphabetic writing

00:41:32.810 --> 00:41:34.951
not changing much since the invention

00:41:34.951 --> 00:41:39.133
of the printing press in the 15th century,

00:41:40.338 --> 00:41:44.980
modern technologies, particularly
social media technologies

00:41:44.980 --> 00:41:47.460
are having a very rapid
and profound effect

00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:50.860
on writing practices in the 21st century.

00:41:50.860 --> 00:41:53.200
Interestingly, many of
these new technologies

00:41:53.200 --> 00:41:56.160
are making less use of
alphabetic writing systems

00:41:56.160 --> 00:41:59.420
and more use once again of pictographs,

00:41:59.420 --> 00:42:00.663
as can be seen here

00:42:00.663 --> 00:42:05.410
comparing the Egyptian
hieroglyphics of 3100 BC

00:42:05.410 --> 00:42:07.980
to a thank you note I recently
received from my niece

00:42:07.980 --> 00:42:11.747
that says, "Dinner was awesome.

00:42:11.747 --> 00:42:13.737
"It was a gift.

00:42:13.737 --> 00:42:14.877
"Thanks."

00:42:19.540 --> 00:42:21.690
And another example,

00:42:21.690 --> 00:42:24.200
a Chinese pictograph for medical marijuana

00:42:24.200 --> 00:42:27.334
originally from 10,000 years ago

00:42:27.334 --> 00:42:31.803
and a clip art symbol for
medical marijuana from 2017.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:35.669
Since the 15th century,

00:42:35.669 --> 00:42:38.530
despite many changes in spoken English

00:42:38.530 --> 00:42:41.900
from old English to middle English

00:42:41.900 --> 00:42:45.170
to early modern and late modern English,

00:42:45.170 --> 00:42:48.958
like here it says, then
she went to speak the

00:42:48.958 --> 00:42:51.003
whatever English tongue,

00:42:52.700 --> 00:42:56.680
written English has
used the same 26 letters

00:42:56.680 --> 00:43:00.823
to represent the 44 sounds
of English until now.

00:43:01.670 --> 00:43:03.997
The bottom line reads,

00:43:03.997 --> 00:43:08.997
"Then she went to speak this
digital age English tongue."

00:43:12.637 --> 00:43:15.844
Neuroscientists like me
who specialize in reading

00:43:15.844 --> 00:43:18.120
are frequently asked these days

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:20.930
how might these rapid
technological changes

00:43:20.930 --> 00:43:23.403
in reading and writing
affect the human mind?

00:43:24.400 --> 00:43:26.280
My colleague, Dr. Maryanne Wolf,

00:43:26.280 --> 00:43:28.250
focuses on exactly this question

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:31.170
in her new book Reader, Come Home.

00:43:31.170 --> 00:43:34.080
I'd like to close with some
of the profound insights

00:43:34.080 --> 00:43:35.603
from this timely book.

00:43:36.867 --> 00:43:40.727
"As we move from a literary
and word-based culture

00:43:40.727 --> 00:43:45.091
"into a far faster paced
digital and screen-based one,

00:43:45.091 --> 00:43:49.253
"we face an existential
dilemma in this new millennium.

00:43:51.717 --> 00:43:53.517
"There are many things that would be lost

00:43:53.517 --> 00:43:56.527
"if we slowly lose the cognitive patience

00:43:56.527 --> 00:43:59.447
"to immerse ourselves in the worlds

00:43:59.447 --> 00:44:00.897
"that are created by books

00:44:00.897 --> 00:44:03.667
"and the lives, feelings,
thoughts and insights

00:44:03.667 --> 00:44:06.160
"of the characters who inhabit them."

00:44:06.160 --> 00:44:08.430
In a culture that increasingly rewards

00:44:08.430 --> 00:44:11.350
immediacy, ease and efficiency,

00:44:11.350 --> 00:44:13.800
the demanding time and effort involved

00:44:13.800 --> 00:44:16.409
in what Dr. Wolfe refers
to as, deep reading

00:44:16.409 --> 00:44:20.470
make it an increasingly embattled entity.

00:44:20.470 --> 00:44:24.800
In closing, I ask each of you
to consider this question,

00:44:24.800 --> 00:44:27.610
will the very plasticity
of the literate brain

00:44:27.610 --> 00:44:31.360
as it begins to reflect the
characteristics of digital media

00:44:31.360 --> 00:44:33.360
that we and our children are increasingly

00:44:33.360 --> 00:44:35.140
immersing ourselves in

00:44:35.140 --> 00:44:37.522
precipitate the atrophy

00:44:37.522 --> 00:44:40.730
of our most essential thought processes,

00:44:40.730 --> 00:44:44.810
sustained attention, critical analysis,

00:44:44.810 --> 00:44:46.680
empathy and reflection

00:44:46.680 --> 00:44:48.960
and indeed wisdom,

00:44:48.960 --> 00:44:51.850
to the detriment of democratic societies

00:44:51.850 --> 00:44:53.900
that critically depend on these,

00:44:53.900 --> 00:44:55.930
the most essential characteristics

00:44:55.930 --> 00:44:58.940
of the enlightened, literate individual?

00:44:58.940 --> 00:44:59.999
Thank you.

00:44:59.999 --> 00:45:02.999
(audience applause)

00:45:07.277 --> 00:45:09.944
(upbeat music)

